03747nam a22005655i 9780520354760DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20201993cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203547607 a10.1525/97805203547602doi  a(DE-B1597)570232  a(OCoLC)1198931811  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0010002bisacsh1 aAdam, Heribert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Opening of the Apartheid Mind :bOptions for the New South Africa /cKogila Moodley, Heribert Adam.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on Southern Africa ;v500 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRefusing to be governed by what is fashionable or inoffensive, Heribert Adam and Kogila Moodley frankly address the passions and rationalities that drive politics in post-apartheid South Africa. They argue that the country's quest for democracy is widely misunderstood and that public opinion abroad relies on stereotypes of violent tribalism and false colonial analogies. Adam and Moodley criticize the personality cult surrounding Nelson Mandela and the accolades accorded F. W. de Klerk. They reject the black-versus-white conflict and substitute sober analysis and strategic pragmatism for the moral outrage that typifies so much writing about South Africa. Believing that the best expression of solidarity emanates from sympathetic but candid criticism, they pose challenging questions for the African National Congress and Nelson Mandela. They give in-depth coverage to political violence, the ANC-South African Communist Party alliance, Inkatha, and other controversial topics as well. The authors do not propose a solution that will guarantee a genuinely democratic South Africa. What they offer is an understanding 